      <!-- Section 1 -->
      <section id="what-it-means" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>What Ecommerce AI Optimisation Means</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>Ecommerce AI optimisation is the discipline of structuring online store content and data so generative AI engines cite specific products and brands in response to shopping and research queries.</strong>
          It is a distinct practice from traditional ecommerce SEO, which targets ranking positions in Google's blue-link results. AI engines do not rank results —
          they generate synthesised answers, and the products that appear in those answers are selected through mechanisms that standard on-page SEO does not address.
        </p>

        <p>
          The commercial significance is growing rapidly. Shoppers increasingly use AI assistants at the research and shortlisting stage of a purchase journey.
          A buyer considering a new espresso machine who asks Perplexity for "the best semi-automatic espresso machines for home use" receives a curated answer citing
          three to five products by name, with brief justifications. The brands cited gain immediate consideration. The brands not cited may never enter the
          consideration set at all — even if their products rank on page one of traditional search.
        </p>

        <p>
          Ecommerce AI optimisation operates at three levels: the product page (structured data, specifications, review integration), the category page
          (editorial content, comparison tables, buying guides), and the brand level (entity authority, citation footprint, cross-platform presence).
          Effective programmes address all three in parallel, as weakness at any level creates gaps in AI citation coverage.
        </p>

        <p>
          This page focuses specifically on online stores — brands whose primary channel is direct-to-consumer or marketplace ecommerce.
          If your brand operates physical retail alongside an online presence, see our guide to <a href="/geo-for-retail/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">GEO for retail</a>,
          which covers the additional considerations for omnichannel and brick-and-mortar discovery in AI answers.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 2 -->
      <section id="how-ai-discovers-products" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>How AI Engines Discover Ecommerce Products</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>AI engines discover ecommerce products through three primary mechanisms: structured data extraction, retrieval-augmented generation, and training data patterns.</strong>
          Each mechanism requires a different optimisation approach, and the dominant mechanism varies by platform.
        </p>

        <h3>Structured Data Extraction</h3>
        <p>
          When an AI crawler visits a product page, it processes the HTML and JSON-LD markup to extract structured attributes: product name, brand, price,
          availability, aggregate rating, and review count. Pages with complete, valid Product schema allow AI systems to extract this data with high
          confidence. Pages without schema — or with partial, malformed schema — are parsed heuristically, which produces less accurate and less consistent
          data in the AI system's index. For ecommerce, structured data is not a nice-to-have; it is the primary signal layer through which products
          enter AI knowledge bases.
        </p>

        <h3>Retrieval-Augmented Generation</h3>
        <p>
          RAG-based platforms — Perplexity, Bing Copilot, Google AI Overviews — retrieve live web content when processing shopping queries. The retrieval
          query generated from a user's question determines which pages are fetched. Pages that are retrieved are then passed to the language model as
          context, and the model cites the products and brands described in those pages. For RAG retrieval, the page needs to be indexable by the platform's
          crawler, relevant to the query by content, and structured clearly enough for the model to extract specific product claims without ambiguity.
        </p>

        <h3>Training Data Patterns</h3>
        <p>
          Products and brands frequently referenced in product reviews, comparison articles, buyer's guides, and editorial content across the web are more
          likely to have strong parametric representation in model weights. A brand cited in twenty independent product review publications is more likely
          to appear in training-data-derived responses than a brand of equal quality that has not attracted editorial coverage. Building editorial
          citation footprint — through PR, affiliate partnerships, and review outreach — strengthens the training data layer independent of technical optimisation.
        </p>
      </section>

