            means ensuring your product and category pages meet Google's retrieval and quality criteria, with complete structured data and
            editorially credible content.
          </p>
          <p>
            For a broader introduction to GEO strategy across all platforms, see our guide to
            <a href="/generative-engine-optimisation/">generative engine optimisation</a> and explore our
            <a href="/geo-services/">GEO services</a>.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 4: Structured Data -->
      <section id="structured-data" class="anchor-top mb-16">
        <div class="prose-dark">
          <h2>Structured Data for Ecommerce Product Pages</h2>
          <p>
            <strong>Complete Product schema is the single highest-leverage technical intervention for ecommerce AI citation.</strong>
            Without it, AI systems must parse product attributes heuristically — a process that produces inconsistent, incomplete, and sometimes
            inaccurate data representations. With it, AI engines can extract product details with high confidence and cite them accurately
            in generated shopping answers.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="mt-8 space-y-6">

          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">Core Product Schema Attributes</h3>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              Every product page should implement <code>@type: "Product"</code> with at minimum: <code>name</code>, <code>brand</code>,
              <code>description</code>, <code>sku</code>, <code>image</code>, <code>offers</code> (with <code>price</code>,
              <code>priceCurrency</code>, <code>availability</code>), and <code>aggregateRating</code> (with <code>ratingValue</code>
              and <code>reviewCount</code>). Missing any of these leaves data gaps that reduce citation confidence.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">Product Specifications</h3>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              AI engines frequently cite specific product specifications when answering comparative queries. Supplement the base schema with
              <code>additionalProperty</code> items for technical specifications: dimensions, weight, materials, compatibility, certifications.
              Present the same specifications in a visible HTML table on the page — AI systems weight specifications more highly when they
              appear in both structured data and visible content.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">ItemList Schema for Category Pages</h3>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              Category pages that list multiple products benefit from <code>@type: "ItemList"</code> schema that enumerates the products
              in the list with <code>ListItem</code> elements. This allows AI systems to understand the relationships between
              the category page and individual products, and is particularly valuable for "best X" category pages that AI engines
              retrieve when answering recommendation queries.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">BreadcrumbList and Site Structure</h3>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              <code>BreadcrumbList</code> schema on every product and category page provides AI systems with context about the site's
              taxonomy — where a product sits within the category hierarchy. This improves the accuracy of categorical references
              in AI answers and signals the organisational structure of the store to knowledge graph systems.
            </p>
          </div>

        </div>

        <div class="prose-dark mt-8">
          <p>
            For detailed implementation guidance on all schema types relevant to AI citation, including worked examples
            for ecommerce use cases, see our technical guide to <a href="/schema-markup-ai/">schema markup for AI</a>.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 5: Category Pages -->
      <section id="category-content" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>Category Pages as AI Editorial Content</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>Ecommerce category pages must function as editorial content, not just product grids, to be cited by AI engines for "best X" and recommendation queries.</strong>
          The typical category page — a grid of products with filter controls and minimal text — provides nothing for an AI retrieval system to extract
          as a citable answer. A category page rebuilt with editorial intent provides the structured, quotable content that AI engines need.
        </p>

        <h3>Buying Guides and Definitive Recommendations</h3>
        <p>
          Lead each category page with a buying guide section that answers the most common questions in the category explicitly.
          "What should I look for when buying a running shoe?" with a clear, structured answer. "Who is this category best suited to?"
          with specific use-case breakdowns. These sections match the query patterns AI engines retrieve for research-stage shopping queries,
          and the explicit question-answer structure makes them highly citable.
        </p>

        <h3>Comparison Tables</h3>
        <p>
          Structured comparison tables comparing the top products in a category by key attributes — price, key specification, use case, rating —
          are among the most frequently cited elements in AI shopping answers. A well-structured HTML table with <code>scope="col"</code> headers
          and consistent attribute columns provides the comparative data that AI systems extract when answering "best X for Y" queries.
          Each row should reference a specific, real product with accurate attributes.
        </p>

        <h3>Use-Case Segmentation</h3>
        <p>
          AI engines regularly answer segmented queries: "best laptop for students", "best espresso machine for beginners", "best running shoe
          for flat feet". Category pages that explicitly address these use-case segments — with a dedicated subheading and recommended products
          for each — are far more likely to be cited for segmented queries than pages that present an undifferentiated product grid.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 6: Reviews -->
      <section id="review-signals" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>Review Signals and Social Proof for AI Citation</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>Review signals are a critical and frequently overlooked component of ecommerce AI citation.</strong>
          AI engines use review data as a quality proxy when determining which products to cite in response to "best X" queries.
          A product with a high aggregate rating, a substantial review count, and reviews visible in structured data is treated as
          more credible and more citable than an equivalent product with sparse review data.
        </p>

        <h3>On-Site Review Schema</h3>
        <p>
          Implement <code>Review</code> items within your Product schema, and ensure <code>aggregateRating</code> is always populated
          with accurate <code>ratingValue</code>, <code>bestRating</code>, <code>worstRating</code>, and <code>reviewCount</code>.
          AI retrieval systems extract these values and use them when generating comparative product answers. Outdated or missing
          review counts create data gaps that suppress citation frequency.
        </p>

        <h3>Third-Party Review Platforms</h3>
        <p>
          AI training data and RAG retrieval both benefit from review presence on authoritative third-party platforms. Google Customer Reviews,
          Trustpilot, and category-specific review platforms (Feefo, Reviews.io) contribute to the editorial citation footprint that
          improves parametric representation in model training data. Brands with consistent, high-volume review presence across multiple
          platforms are more likely to be cited as credible options than brands whose reviews exist only on their own site.
        </p>

        <h3>Editorial Review Coverage</h3>
        <p>
          Independent editorial reviews — in technology publications, niche interest media, affiliate comparison sites, and YouTube review
          channels — are among the highest-value citation sources for ecommerce AI visibility. An editorial review that names and evaluates
          your product specifically, and is published on a domain with reasonable authority, contributes both to RAG retrieval (the review page
          can be fetched and cited) and to training data representation (the review adds to the corpus of documents mentioning your product
          in a positive, authoritative context).
        </p>
